comments.message: This is reusing the same variable (PKG) as the enclosing while loop. It looks like it should work, because the old value isn't needed anymore, but it could cause confusion and future bugs if changes are made here later.
Thanks Jen, does this change address your comments? Or do you think PKG should not be changing within the loop?

Ideally, I don't think PKG should be changing within the loop, to be safe.
For example, I think you may already have a bug here, since PKG is used later to update the MISSING_LIST; unless the intention is to not add it to the MISSING_LIST in this case (but this would be a very subtle way of achieving that goal).
I think you need double quotes around that otherwise that would fail if it's empty.

Does this change solve this scenario?

The build depends on python script that starts with these lines:

    #!/usr/bin/env python
    import jinja2

On Ubuntu 18.04 "/usr/bin/env python" resolves to a python 2.7 interpreter and on Ubuntu 20.04, it resolves to a python 3.x interpreter.  So on Ubuntu 18.04 you need the package "python-jinja", but on Ubuntu 20.04 you need "python3-jinja".  Also note that "python-jinja" *does* exist in Ubuntu, but it will provide a library for a python version that the build doesn't run.

Oops!  This:

> Also note that "python-jinja" *does* exist in Ubuntu

Was supposed to say:

> Also note that "python-jinja" *does* exist in Ubuntu 20.04
grep will output text that matches, which could result in clutter in your script's output (i.e., the build logs). It's a good habit to get into to redirect grep's stdout to /dev/null.
hi Jen, the "-q" option for grep silences output
it looks like it breaks from the loop on the first PACKAGE that does NOT match an available package in the apt-cache. Isn't this the opposite of what we want?

comments.message:
I think there was an idea to do a 2 step checking here to be able to clarify what's not working.

I imagine that __check_credentials is used on the manifest repository, which is accessible to any person that has a ssh key registered on GitHub since it's a public repository.

That check by itself would not catch issues related to access to private repositories.

I created repository https://github.com/legatoproject/test-access that would only be accessible to people that have properly setup access.

So in the "external" use case the first check would test access to test-access repository (url = self._url.value.replace("manifest", "test-access") ?)

If is not accessible, then you can test access to self._url.value (manifest repo?).

If manifest repo is accessible => it means that only the private repos are inaccessible => message = "Repository %s on GitHub is not accessible, please visit https://swi-license.legato.io/docs to request access."

Otherwise => it means that GitHub is not accessible at all, which is likely a user setup issue.
message = "Unable to access GitHub through SSH, please make sure that you have a GitHub user account and that your SSH key is registered on that account. More information available at https://swi-license.legato.io/docs"

For the link, you can use https://swi-license.legato.io/docs .
I will update that link to point it to the docs, and that way we have something static.

I had a feeling something wasn't right.

The new patch revision should satisfy all requirements.
You can remove 'docs' so it points to https://swi-license.legato.io/ directly.

comments.message:
Maybe I'm wrong but I don't like to unecessarily extend the execution graph of Make.
I would directly use

shellcheck:	
	echo "Analyzing scripts with shellcheck..."
	shellcheck $(SHELLCHECK_OPTS) $(shell find $(PWD) -name "*.sh" | tr "\n" " ")
Using directly is better for checking many scripts as same time

Why don't we enable this one?
Doc: https://github.com/koalaman/shellcheck/wiki/SC2001

I would prefer this directive disable only in problematic files, not for all files.
Like 
  # shellcheck disable=SC2148

We should write a report here, 
A report is easier to read after a failing job instead of parsing the console output (Need to update the list of artifacts in jenkins configuration)
See shellcheck help:
  -f FORMAT         --format=FORMAT          Output format (checkstyle, gcc, json, tty)

Have you tested it because *exec* case should be a case where you whould not use "" for $ARGS

Example: See how myexec1 prints _1 2 3_ because it only sees one argument

(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ cat myecho.sh 
#!/bin/bash

for A in "$@"; do 
        echo -n "_${A}_"
done
echo ""
(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ cat myexec1.sh 
#!/bin/bash

ARGS="1 2 3"
exec ./myecho.sh "$ARGS"
(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ cat myexec2.sh 
#!/bin/bash

ARGS="4 5 6"
exec ./myecho.sh $ARGS
(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ ./myexec1.sh 
_1 2 3_
(venv) seb@Guldan:~ $ ./myexec2.sh 
_4__5__6_
I don't think 2068 is a problem here, traces are only strings message, can be double quoted
Should be written trace "Checking ${input} existence" and so the 2086 disable is not needed
why this var is not double quoted?
end the double quote after .json for better readability
Why not double quoting this variable?

Patch Set 5:

Hi Lars,

Please get my comment in below:
- Because swi-vscode-support just relates to the VSCode extension, using Leaf on Terminal doesn't require this swi-vscode-support package. So I think we don't want to install it for every SDK package as a depending package.
- In addition, this change will not affect to the previous SDK packages. We will still need to install the swi-vscode-support package manually if we use this previous SDK packages.

I think that you can consider the following solution:
On VSCode, when user creates (or selects) a Leaf profile in Leaf view, if this Leaf profile doesn't contain the latest swi-vscode-support package, the VSCode extension will install it automatically.
For more user friendly, the VSCode extension can popup a message to recommend user to install it. If user chooses OK, the swi-vscode-support package will be installed.
So this improvement will be implemented by VSCode extension instead of the SDK leaf packages.

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> Hi Lars,
> 
> Please get my comment in below:
> - Because swi-vscode-support just relates to the VSCode extension, using Leaf on Terminal doesn't require this swi-vscode-support package. So I think we don't want to install it for every SDK package as a depending package.
> - In addition, this change will not affect to the previous SDK packages. We will still need to install the swi-vscode-support package manually if we use this previous SDK packages.
> 
> I think that you can consider the following solution:
> On VSCode, when user creates (or selects) a Leaf profile in Leaf view, if this Leaf profile doesn't contain the latest swi-vscode-support package, the VSCode extension will install it automatically.
> For more user friendly, the VSCode extension can popup a message to recommend user to install it. If user chooses OK, the swi-vscode-support package will be installed.
> So this improvement will be implemented by VSCode extension instead of the SDK leaf packages.

I've discussed this with Sarra, and it was agreed that we should automatically install the swi-vscode-support_latest package for all cases.  It is not unforeseeable to have someone set-up their Leaf packages outside the IDE, and then decide to open the IDE and continue working using it.

As for having this take affect with older SDK packages, this would be the best.  Unfortunately, not easy to implement.   As such, we will only provide this for newer SDKs.   For older SDKs, the user will still need to manually install the vscode support package.

> - Because swi-vscode-support just relates to the VSCode extension, using Leaf on Terminal doesn't require this swi-vscode-support package. So I think we don't want to install it for every SDK package as a depending package.
> - In addition, this change will not affect to the previous SDK packages. We will still need to install the swi-vscode-support package manually if we use this previous SDK packages.
> 
> I think that you can consider the following solution:
> On VSCode, when user creates (or selects) a Leaf profile in Leaf view, if this Leaf profile doesn't contain the latest swi-vscode-support package, the VSCode extension will install it automatically.
> For more user friendly, the VSCode extension can popup a message to recommend user to install it. If user chooses OK, the swi-vscode-support package will be installed.
> So this improvement will be implemented by VSCode extension instead of the SDK leaf packages.

Hi Tung,

I just wanted to touch on your comments,

We decided to go through with the change because by definition an SDK "is a collection of software development tools in one installable package". It is not necessary for all tools to be utilized and a user can safely ignore the vscode-support-package if he does not wish to use it. The main reason for this change is to make it easier for users to start using vscode. Unfortunately, old sdk's will still need  to manually install the swi-vscode-support package but will promote the use of newer sdks.

comments.message:
Why not have this return 1 or 0 instead of what it's doing now?
It seems weird to match the output against artifactFileName. I'm not sure how that works in Http mode.

The __check_existence returns an artifactFileName if it's available in artifact path (the http mode has the same output). For this case, if the extraOption is --optional and the output of __check_existence is different from artifactFileName, it means that the optional package is not available, we skip fetching it. otherwise, we keep the original process.

It doesn't return but prints the result on stdout, that is captured by $().

I'm still not sure why we can't do something like:

if test "$extraOption" = --optional -a ! __check_existence "$1"; then
    ...
fi

That would imply that __check_existence returns 0 in case of PASS and != 0 (such as 1) instead of FAIL.

Something like __check_existence "$1" "${artifactFileName}" would also be fine with me if you do the compare inside.

Patch Set 7:

> Patch Set 6:
> 
> (1 comment)

You're correct. The latest patch bases on your solution but I have modified it in the following parts: 
- When the user refuses to update the latest version for swicwe and swiflash, the leaf package installing will be exited with error code 2. (The reason is: if the installing is continue, the original issue of LETOOLS-899 can be happened again)
- Add "-y" flag for the apt upgrade command.

Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

> Patch Set 7:
> 
> > Patch Set 6:
> > 
> > (1 comment)
> 
> You're correct. The latest patch bases on your solution but I have modified it in the following parts: 
> - When the user refuses to update the latest version for swicwe and swiflash, the leaf package installing will be exited with error code 2. (The reason is: if the installing is continue, the original issue of LETOOLS-899 can be happened again)
> - Add "-y" flag for the apt upgrade command.

Good catch for the second point.

But I don't totally agree with your first argument. If for some reason, the user does really not want to upgrade its swiflash/swicwe, then we should not prevent him to install the leaf SDK or whatever he is installing.

Because the script is not 100% sure that there is an upgrade, and if the upgrade (if there is one) is mandatory to avoid the LETOOLS-899 issue. 

So let the user decide if he wants to upgrade its tools, if he decides not to, then
- he may encounter the LETOOLS-899 issue but he can reinstall the leaf package and choose to upgrade its tools
- he may not encounter the LETOOLS-899 issue, and I think we should allow this case by not exiting on line 126

Maybe @slyford you can give us your thoughts from a UX point of view?

About the implement in patch 7, I just worry about a case when we force user to upgrade swi tools. If the latest swi tools (swicwe and swiflash) is not compatible with a leaf package, there is no way to work around when apt-checker always try to install the  latest swi tools. Although I think the newer version always be better than the older version, but this issue also can be happened.

To avoid this risk, I updated a new patch. It just raises the information instead of exit the package installing when the user refuse to upgrade the latest version for swi tools. 

I also agree that some users will be more comfortable when they can be free to choose updating swi tools or not.

comments.message:
As we are working on multiple debian based distribution, a strict equal may not be used.
For example, requiring some lib with a fixed version "1.9.1-0" has very little chance to work on more than one distribution (is there any package with same version in debian9/debian10/ubuntu1904/ubuntu1404 ... ?)
Maybe we shouldn't implement it to avoid potential problems.

Regarding the complexity of the code, Shell should not be the best language to have a maintainable code.
Python could be an option, what do you think?

THis implementation will exit after upgrading.
But we have to handle the case, some packages need to be installed AND swiflash and/or swicwe need to be upgraded.
You can check a quick implementation I did https://gerrit.legato/c/leaf-packages/+/53226

I think that we should check the out of date package version after $MISSING_LIST is checked and installed. So we will not worry about the missing packages.
I have updated patch 5 to execute _checkAndUpgradePackages after $MISSING_LIST is checked and installed. So we just upgrade swicwe and swiflash if they have been installed but have not been in the latest version

The problem with your algo is that apt policy works with a cache that you are not sure is uptodate.

For example, take the use case there is no apt package that I need to install.
Then I won't trigger any *apt update* before your apt policy so you cannot be sure there is not update available.

That is why I skipped the apt policy to detect newer version because you need to run *sudo apt update* before to be sure that apt policy is relevant.
So in my patch I choose to directly run *apt update && apt install --upgrade*

Just to be clear.
If you want to use the *apt policy* you have to run *sudo apt update* before.
But to run *sudo apt update* to have to be interactive to ask the user.
Then if you detect a newer version with the *apt policy* you have to ask the user a second time to update the packages.
Which means one or two interactions.

With the solution in my patch, I don't detect newer version with *apt policy* but I ask the user only once which  is a better UX in my opinion.

comments.message: Sample Legato application demonstrating data exchange between an embedded Legato application and the AirVantage server, over the LWM2M protocol.
I packaged some apps just to have some content but apps will be packaged in another repository so I will remove these samples in the next patch.
Sample Legato application demonstrating an LWM2M Control app communicating with AirVantage.
Sample Legato application demonstrating a simple app running inside a sandbox that prints information about files or directories specified from the command line.
Sample Legato Application demonstrating the Data Hub - the central hub for the flow of control system data, such as sensor input and actuator setpoints.
Sample Legato application demonstrating how to test an eCall session.
Sample Legato application demonstrating CF3 module GPIO
Sample Legato application demonstrating CF3 GPIO Selective Suspend, showing how GPIO can be used to wake the device from the selective suspend state.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the usage of the GNSS service along with a few other services and APIs to find nearby points of interest using reverse-geocoding, along with their distances.
Sample Legato application demonstrating two components communicating over IPC.
Sample Legato application demonstrating remote-procedure calls between two Legato systems using RPC bindings.
Sample Legato application demonstrating opening a data connection and libcurl usage.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the lighttpd http server serving sh and Python scripts as pages over https.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the use of interactive apps through an application process's standard streams.
Sample Legato application demonstrating interaction with the modem, along with sending and receiving SMS messages.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the MQTT messaging protocol.
Sample Legato application demonstrating Layered Publish Subscribe by performing sensor temperature monitoring.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the use of a shell script and some common utilities within a sandboxed app.
Sample Legato application demonstrating usage of the SMS service.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the usage of the SMS service along with a few other services and APIs in order to perform SMS messaging operations.
Sample Legato application demonstrating streaming audio over IP.
Sample Legato application demonstrating using the Ultra Low Power Mode API.
Sample Legato application demonstrating the usage of the voicecall service along with a few other services and APIs to establish voice communication using an activated SIM card.
"Sample Legato application showing how to monitor a critical process with a watchdog"

comments.message: useless class ton store one constant?

You can iterate over key,value with 

for setting_id, setting in self.wm.get_settings().items()

Actually, I just need to work with keys here.
Changed to lambda processing

Optional args user_env=None, ws_env=None, pf_env=None are for internal optimisations.
When you call get_setting*s* to query multiple settings, it is used to avoid create n times the scopes.

You should not pass these args (or at least name them with ws_env=... pf_env=...), but I recomment not passing them (I maybe should have implemented a private method which use these args not to have them in the public api.
Maybe reword the description to give more sense?

comments.message: Would be nice to add indent using spaces for readability.

Yeah; the point is I already had troubles by trying to make that kind of things looking nice in a Makefile, and there was some weird behavior with the vars definition not taken into account, etc...
so... now by default I keep things ugly but functional :(

I think it's just that by default, most editors use tabs for Makefile, and if you use the tab key it will indent using tabs, which doesn't work as it things it's a rule.

But if you indent manually using spaces that should work.

So it seems that jasmine2 is actually not where they deliver stuff.
Instead it's on \\usnwk-fl01\groups\Engineering\Dev\Programmable-Connectivity-UnReleased\3G\REL_R14.0.2.002\images\public for instance.

CARMD-EV-LXCIM_sa (and I) don't have access at the moment.
We talked about it with Chris yesterday, I think the action is on his side, but should follow up on that.

It's just for testing; the input path will be an input parameter on the Jenkins job
At the moment, the resources are also provided on //jasmine2 (because I neither have access to \\usnwk-fl01 and I asked Chris to put the files elsewhere :-) )
I see, sounds good, and yeah I'm a bit in the same situation, hopefully Chris will unlock that quickly.
I've opened a Help Desk ticket to provide access to this folder, still awaiting completion.

comments.message:
Even if this is an internal tool, having long options make code more readable & maintainable.
Plus as it will be invoked by scripts and not by a user, UX will remain the same?

Last point, we should try to keep short option (1 dash) one letter long.

Added long options.
Indeed, this is not called by users.
Keeping the old options anyway, because we have legacy scripts on the field that use them, and we can't break the interface.

Just need to check if the var is set
Added a len test to be sure

You should build the command to make it easier to read
Maybe using "".format() would be better?

Example (does not work, just an example): 
"repo init {user}@{host}:/repo/{path} {target}".format(
  user="jdoe",
  location="somewhere",
  host="legato.io")
You can set CWD in subprocess API to avoid cd in shell.
You can use match as you *search* with ^ and $
You can use subprocess.DEVNULL to avoid >/dev/null?
We should maintain a map<HOST, List<IP_PREFIX>>

miss indent?
This methode can return None?
Because if repoType is not internal nor external, None will be returned
Yes, the method can return None (which is an error case later diagnosed by generic code)

str.format could be nicer than % here.

Build a dict with variables
values = {'product': product, 'version': self.getVersion()  ... and all variables you may use}

After you just format
"{product}/tags/{version}/foo.xml".format(**variables)
and you can use your variables multiple times.

Update swi-cloneutils to use internal mirrors and add master remote

1/ When possible, clone from Gerrit mirrors available within SWI.

2/ Provide a 'master' remote in each repositories as to make it
possible to push through SSH given that only master servers can
accept contributions.

3/ Prepare for the external infrastructure with multiple mirrors
reacheable across the world (reacheable at gerrit.legato.io) and
the limit master servers (reacheable at master.gerrit.legato.io).

comments.message: Do we need to commit that?
We shouldn't commit that, many users uses venv for python for example
i'm not sure but in case of no args are given when using 'append', len() == 0 but var is never None

Maybe to use leaf error printing, we should write scripts in python ...
IDK if code will be more readable or not, shell has its advantages, but you seem to do some string building which is easier in python.
Do we need this binary for that? maybe a shared lub or an util should be enough?

Couldn't we handle --verbose ?

You can declare something like
add_argument("--verbose", dest="verbosity", action="store_const", metavar="HINT",
,const=Versbosity.VERBOSE, default=Verbosity.DEFAULT)
You can declare both -v and -q parsers as store_const and stode Verbosity and directly get the args.verbosity .
Unfortunately no, since I need the real verbosity below at line 133 to initialize WorkspaceManager
Shouldn't we choose a more specific name? python-src, python-lib ?

comments.message: Shouldn't the clone package moved out of prereq folder since its not a prereq anymore?
I cannot see where this script is used?

It's called from legacy packages that are currently requiring swi-cloneutils_1.0
These packages are in production today and won't be replaced.
(e.g. template that was used to build them: http://cgit-legato/leaf-packages.git/tree/sdk/legato-src.json?h=181005)

since set -u is not set, you should check $DEST is set or not?
Plus you should use DQ?
(shellcheck)

the *if* line should be on the next line (same for other cases)
Then this bloc would be aligned with the *swi-linux* code block and improve readability

code from case block should be indented.
If all blocks have one line, I understand that it could looks better, but here not every case has only one line.
Almost no path var is double quoted

Why executing all command in one with && ?
Doesn't make already stops on first error?

Maybe it would be easier to build (and debug) appending args like:
TEMPLATE_ARG=""
if test -f "$FILE"; then
  TEMPLATE_ARG="$TEMPLATE_ARG --append \"$FILE\""
fi

Maybe permissions could be set by tar itself
cf https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18130195/setting-file-permissions-on-contents-of-tarfile

comments.message: There is no real coding conventions for shell, there may be more conventions than the number of shell developpers, but this case loop (and the next more) is hard to read IMO
Why isn't this variable prefixed by SWI_ like the LINUX_SRC ?

"legato" doesn't need to be namespaced as is it expected to be more or less independent from the Sierra Wireless branding.
On the contrary, we're providing a "Sierra Wireless" linux distribution.

Out of scope remarq here... 
I'm not confortable with having theses scripts packaged outside -src package...
It make impossible to manually reproduce the install steps as the prereq folder has been removed.
We may have to manually run these for example trying to reproduce an unwanted behaviour on a client workspace ...

I definitely see your point.
That being said, this is supposed to be a temporary way of handling this, as it is convenient to be able to changing the cloning behavior without having to rebuild the packages; and this part is not totally in its definitive design at the moment...
